{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492772"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:44:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:44:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1153"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1153"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.43,0.08,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1153"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111095"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1153"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1153"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93218"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1356"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2015"},{"type":"tags","id":"2227"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5820"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18234"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43063"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44337"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111095"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-day history of upper respiratory tract symptoms, myalgia, and fever. He has been on a cruise ship for seven days. In the past two days, he has developed a productive cough with yellow sputum. He has a history of asthma and takes fluticasone/salmeterol inhaler and salbutamol inhaler when required. He takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly unwell. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 130/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 38.0\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals right midzone crepitations without wheeze. A viral swab is positive for Influenza A. His chest X-ray shows right middle lobe consolidation (Image). \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oseltamivir","Oral antibiotics","Oral prednisolone","Nebulised salbutamol","Ipratropium bromide"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of community acquired pneumonia complicating influenza A infection. The development of productive cough with yellow sputum and radiological evidence of right middle lobe consolidation strongly suggests secondary bacterial pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case the patient does not have any features that indicate the need for a hospital admission, such as tachypnea, tachycardia, hypotension, acute onset confusion, SpO2 \u0026lt;92% on room air or multi-lobar involvement on chest XR. In these cases commencing \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment. Empiric therapy should cover common respiratory pathogens including \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E, which are frequent causes of post-influenza bacterial pneumonia with amoxicillin a common example of an appropriate empirical antibiotic in these cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOseltamivir\u003C/strong\u003E, an antiviral, would have been appropriate if started within 48 hours of symptom onset. However, the patient presented after six days of symptoms, beyond the window where neuraminidase inhibitors have proven benefit in reducing symptom duration and severity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there were features of acute asthma exacerbation. However, the absence of wheeze and presence of focal consolidation make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised salbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as there are no features of bronchospasm. The patient\u0027s respiratory symptoms are more likely due to pneumonia rather than asthma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIpratropium bromide\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticholinergic bronchodilator that would be appropriate for bronchospasm, which is not a feature in this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBacterial pneumonia is a well-recognised complication of influenza infection, occurring in up to 25% of cases. The virus damages the respiratory epithelium, predisposing to secondary bacterial infection. Close monitoring for deterioration and assessment of response to antibiotics is essential.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Community-acquired pneumonia commonly develops as a bacterial superinfection in patients with influenza.","Radiological evidence of consolidation in patients testing positive for viral respiratory tract infection suggests bacterial pneumonia requiring antibiotic therapy."],"references":["Community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) in adults. In: Therapeutic guidelines. 2025 [cited 2025 Aug 8]. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Lanks CW, Musani AI, Hsia DW. Community-acquired Pneumonia and Hospital-acquired Pneumonia. Med Clin N Am 2019; 103:487-501. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30955516/","Regunath H, Oba Y. Community-Acquired Pneumonia. [Updated 2024 Jan 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430749/","Community Acquired Pneumonia (Adults) Clinical Guideline. In SA Health Clinical Practice Guidelines [online]. 2021 [cited 2025 Aug 8]. Available at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/9da8d680432af0a6a631f68cd21c605e/CAP+Clinical+Guideline+%28Adults%29_v2_FINAL_Jan2021+%282%29.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-9da8d680432af0a6a631f68cd21c605e-p4bC5NL"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93218"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1153"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21129"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21129"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JEUtiUxOiBVN7rRZxieEFD52JgxFHy.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JEUtiUxOiBVN7rRZxieEFD52JgxFHy.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":599,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93218"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-08T20:00:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-08T20:01:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1153"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111095"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},